text=(:if authgroup @tas:)%0a%0a(:toggle id=gi show="show grading interface" hide="hide grading interface":)%0a%0a>>id=gi%3c%3c%0a%0a[[GradebookArticles.{$Name}|See article in gradebook]] \\%0a[[{$FullName}?action=diff|See all changes to article]]%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradeitem:)%0a%0a(:foxform Site.FoxForms#gradingcomment:)%0a%0a>>%3c%3c%0a%0a----%0a%0a(:ifend:)%0a%0a[[!PracticeCategory]]%0a%0a!Decipherment of Ancient Written Languages%0a%0a:Author: JoshuaC%0a%0a'''Summary:''' \\%0a%0a[[#summary]]%0a%0aHow are written languages formed and how can ancient written languages be deciphered%0a%0a[[#summaryends]]%0a%0a----%0a[[#content]]%0a%0aI recently read a book that covered the decipherment of Egyptian hieroglyphics. Even though Egyptian scripts had a phonetic component with characters representing distinct sounds, this was an idea that many scholars refused to accept. Instead, they believed that the hieroglyphs only represented ideas. This perception inhibited efforts to decipher the language until the 1800s with the discovery of the Rosetta Stone.%0a%0aWhile not directly related, this got me thinking about how written languages are formed. Why do some languages have characters representing ideas while others have characters which represent distinct sounds? Do most written languages have a mix of both? Other than ideas or distinct sounds, are there other possible features that written languages can represent?%0a%0aThe author of the book also drew parallels between the decipherment of ancient texts and cryptanalysis/codebreaking, in terms of challenges faced, techniques used and approach to the problem. This is a comparison I found really interesting. What are some lessons that each field can take away from each other? Could experts from one field contribute to the other? For example, can mathematicians help in the decipherment of ancient texts?%0a%0a[[#contentends]]%0a----%0a----%0a%0a!!Expansions:%0a[[#expansions]]%0a%0a[[#expansionsend]]%0a%0a----%0a%2